The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, January 12, 2004  LOOSE CHANGE
																								ULIP 71, an open-ended debt-oriented scheme from UTI Mutual Fund, is issuing bonus units in the ratio of one for every ten held (1:10). The record date is February 4. This is ULIPs fourth bonus issue in less than two years. UTI Petro Fund, another UTI Mutual Fund scheme, is paying a dividend of Rs 5.50. The record date is January 23. The scheme has generated a return of 138.47 per centin the last one year.																								Reliance Mutual Fund is launching three sector schemes: power, pharmaceuticals and media. The schemes would invest in both shares and commercial papers. Reliance Mutual Fund says it would look to invest up to 80 per cent of the corpus of these schemes in shares, and the rest in debt instruments. Another new fund expected to hit the market soon is HDFC Universal Fund of Funds that would invest its corpus in various schemes managed by HDFC Mutual Fund. 																								Canara Bank has launched Canmahila, a special personal loan scheme for women. The scheme would allow women aged 18 to 55 years to borrow up to Rs 50,000. Vijaya Bank too has launched a similar credit facility aimed at artisans and the self-employed. Under the Artisan Credit Card Scheme, one could borrow up to Rs 2 lakh, while Swarojgar Credit Card Scheme allows a self-employed individual to draw up to Rs 30,000 in loan.
